```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    cout << "Part one.";
    cout << "Part two.";
    cout << "Part three." << endl;
    cout << "Part four.";
    return 0;
}
```

**Predicted Output:**
```
Part one.Part two.Part three.
Part four.
```

**Explanation:** The first two `cout` statements concatenate their output because no newline is specified. The third `cout` statement prints its string and then inserts an `endl`, moving the cursor to the next line. The fourth `cout` statement then prints its output on that new line.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    cout << "This is a very long sentence that needs to be printed.";
    cout << "And this is another part of the sentence.";
    cout << "Finally, the last part of the sentence.";
    return 0;
}
```

**Predicted Output:**
`This is a very long sentence that needs to be printed.And this is another part of the sentence.Finally, the last part of the sentence.`

**Explanation:** The output will appear on a single logical line because `cout` does not automatically insert newline characters based on the source code's formatting. Each `cout` statement simply appends its output to the current position in the output stream. To force newlines, `endl` or the newline character `\n` must be explicitly used. The visual wrapping on the screen is a function of the display device's width, not an instruction from the program to start a new line.

