solved_examples.solution:
The provided code will not compile because C++ programs require all executable statements to be enclosed within a function, typically the `main()` function, which serves as the entry point of the program. The `cout` statements `cout << "Success\n";` and `cout << " Success\n\n";` are placed outside of any function definition, specifically before `int main() { ... }`. This is syntactically incorrect in C++.

To fix this, all `cout` statements must be moved inside the `main()` function. Additionally, for `cout` to work, the `<iostream>` header must be included at the beginning of the file.

**Corrected Code:**
```cpp
#include <iostream> // Required for cout

int main()
{
    std::cout << "Success\n";
    std::cout << " Success\n\n";
    std::cout << "Success";
    return 0; // Indicate successful execution
}
```
**Explanation of Correction:**
1.  `#include <iostream>`: Added at the top of the file. This preprocessor directive ensures that the declarations for `std::cout` are available to the compiler.
